    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "The example I have currently in mind is when searching in a large text (like a book). I have split my text in chunks that roughly equals a paragraph. In order to display a nice UI, I want to display the matching chunk of text, along with its context (paragraph before and paragraph after). `content`, `after` and `before` are all stored in the same record.\n\nThe thing is, if I have two results like this:\n\n```\nbefore: A\ncontent: B\nafter: C\n```\n\n```\nbefore: B\ncontent: C\nafter: D\n```\n\nYou can see that they are actually two paragraphs following one another. Instead of duplicating the render, I would like to merge them in something like:\n\n```\nbefore: A\ncontent: B + C\nafter: D\n```\n\nTo do that I need to access the full list and merge some hits together before passing it to the rendering.\n\nI just remembered that the `template` and `transformData` keys are really linked, a `transformData` will always be applied to the data when calling the template with the same name. This actually makes a lot of sense and makes the API very predictable. I'm now unsure I really need to change that :)\n\nMaybe using an `allItems` template is actually the best solution. I'm closing the issue for now, but feel free to comment if you have anything other thoughts to add.\n",
    "created_at": "2016-02-08T13:29:05Z",
